                'description' => 'Are you ready for the best falafel you\'ve ever tasted? Falafel are delicious balls of chickpea and herb goodness in Middle Eastern cooking.',
            'content' => '{"@context":"https:\\/\\/schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/","name":"Most Delicious Falafel Recipe (Fried or Baked) | Downshiftology","isPartOf":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/#website"},"primaryImageOfPage":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#primaryimage"},"image":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#primaryimage"},"thumbnailUrl":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/10\\/Falafel-main-2.jpg","datePublished":"2024-09-07T01:26:56+00:00","dateModified":"2024-09-07T01:26:58+00:00","description":"Are you ready for the best falafel you\'ve ever tasted? Falafel are delicious balls of chickpea and herb goodness in Middle Eastern cooking.","breadcrumb":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#breadcrumb"},"inLanguage":"en-US","potentialAction":[{"@type":"ReadAction","target":["https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/"]}],"video":[{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#video"}]},{"@type":"ImageObject","inLanguage":"en-US","@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#primaryimage","url":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/10\\/Falafel-main-2.jpg","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/10\\/Falafel-main-2.jpg","width":1600,"height":1067,"caption":"A plate of falafels and tahini sauce."},{"@type":"BreadcrumbList","@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#breadcrumb","itemListElement":[{"@type":"ListItem","position":1,"name":"Home","item":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/"},{"@type":"ListItem","position":2,"name":"Recipes","item":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/"},{"@type":"ListItem","position":3,"name":"Courses","item":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/courses\\/"},{"@type":"ListItem","position":4,"name":"Dinner","item":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/courses\\/main-course\\/"},{"@type":"ListItem","position":5,"name":"Falafel"}]},{"@type":"WebSite","@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/#website","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/","name":"Downshiftology","description":"Healthy eating, living and travel.","publisher":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/#organization"},"potentialAction":[{"@type":"SearchAction","target":{"@type":"EntryPoint","urlTemplate":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/?s={search_term_string}"},"query-input":"required name=search_term_string"}],"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Organization","@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/#organization","name":"Downshiftology","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","inLanguage":"en-US","@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/#\\/schema\\/logo\\/image\\/","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/06\\/Default-sharing-image.png","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/06\\/Default-sharing-image.png","width":"1200","height":"630","caption":"Downshiftology"},"image":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/#\\/schema\\/logo\\/image\\/"},"sameAs":["http:\\/\\/www.facebook.com\\/downshiftology","https:\\/\\/twitter.com\\/downshiftology","http:\\/\\/www.instagram.com\\/downshiftology","https:\\/\\/www.linkedin.com\\/in\\/lisa-bryan-b0880a\\/","http:\\/\\/www.pinterest.com\\/downshiftology","http:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/c\\/downshiftology"]},{"@type":"Recipe","name":"Most Delicious Falafel Recipe (Fried or Baked)","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Lisa Bryan"},"description":"The best authentic falafel recipe you can make at home! A simple combination of chickpeas, herbs and spices that&#039;s blended together and fried (or baked). They&#039;re crispy, soft and delicious! Watch the video below to see how I make them in my kitchen!","datePublished":"2024-09-06T18:26:56+00:00","image":["https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/10\\/Falafel-main-2.jpg","https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/10\\/Falafel-main-2-500x500.jpg","https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/10\\/Falafel-main-2-500x375.jpg","https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/10\\/Falafel-main-2-480x270.jpg"],"video":{"name":"THE BEST FALAFEL RECIPE | crispy fried and baked falafel (vegan)","description":"Are you ready for the best falafel you\'ve ever tasted (whether fried or baked)? Falafel are delicious balls of chickpea and herb goodness that you find in Middle Eastern cooking.\\n\\nI\'ve had my fair share of falafel on travels through Egypt, Israel and Jordan. I\'ve had them in restaurants and on street corners (the best authentic street food). I\'ve had them stuffed in gluten-free pita and on salads. And I\'ve had them with slight variations and tweaks, though the recipe itself is fairly simple.\\n\\nBut here\'s how you make the best falafel recipe - add tons of herbs (double the normal amount) and a small amount of green pepper. This makes for an addictive flavor that\'s \\"a little something extra\\" but not spicy. Just insanely delicious.\\n\\nFalafel are naturally vegan and vegetarian. You can then deep fry the falafel, pan fry or make baked falafel. It\'s up to you! Just don\'t forget to drizzle with my tahini sauce. ;) Enjoy! \\n\\nFalafel Recipe: http:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/32C96Zu\\n\\nJoin the private Facebook group of fellow Downshifters around the world: https:\\/\\/www.facebook.com\\/groups\\/downshiftologycommunity\\/\\n\\nPRODUCTS MENTIONED:\\nOrganic Chickpeas: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2SpizOW\\nCookie Scoop: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2XTl69Y\\nFalafel Scoop: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2XYvQiv\\nAvocado Oil: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/32MIl4C\\nAvocado Oil Spray: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2SodaaV\\n\\nALWAYS IN MY KITCHEN:\\nCounter Stools: http:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/2tUNvZG\\nVitamix Blender: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2NjFp75\\nSpiralizer: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2N37WRy \\nTea Kettle: http:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2uuNSMp\\nUtensil Holder: http:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/2tVfGaH\\nFlour Jars: http:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/2tV6C5y\\nKnife Set: http:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/2tUGzMa\\nCutting Board: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2Vskgv9\\nGlass Mixing Bowls: https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/2L2hx6O\\n\\nFor everything else I use in my videos, check out the SHOP page on my website: https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/shop\\n\\nThe music I use: https:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/2Ms5nF2 - Great music for YouTubers!\\n\\nWHAT I\'M WEARING:\\nT-Shirt: http:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/2O5NQIm\\nAG Jeans: http:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/2EiNg1N\\nLinen Apron: http:\\/\\/bit.ly\\/2twA32E\\n\\nWEBSITE: https:\\/\\/www.downshiftology.com\\nINSTAGRAM: http:\\/\\/instagram.com\\/downshiftology\\nFACEBOOK: http:\\/\\/facebook.com\\/downshiftology\\nPINTEREST: http:\\/\\/pinterest.com\\/downshiftology\\n\\nDisclaimer: product links may include affiliate links.\\n#falafel #falafelrecipe #vegan","uploadDate":"2019-07-19T14:48:31+00:00","duration":"PT8M50S","thumbnailUrl":"https:\\/\\/i.ytimg.com\\/vi\\/aQD0ndQGpG0\\/hqdefault.jpg","embedUrl":"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/embed\\/aQD0ndQGpG0?feature=oembed","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?v=aQD0ndQGpG0","@type":"VideoObject"},"recipeYield":["18","18 falafel balls"],"prepTime":"PT45M","cookTime":"PT10M","totalTime":"PT55M","recipeIngredient":["1 cup dried chickpeas (soaked overnight (don&#x27;t use canned chickpeas))","\\u00bd cup roughly chopped onion","1 cup roughly chopped parsley (about a one large bunch)","1 cup roughly chopped cilantro (about a one large bunch)","1 small green chile pepper (serrano or jalapeno pepper)","3 garlic cloves","1 teaspoon cumin","1 teaspoon salt","\\u00bd teaspoon cardamom","\\u00bc teaspoon black pepper","2 tablespoons chickpea flour (or other flour)","\\u00bd teaspoon baking soda","oil for frying"],"recipeInstructions":[{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Soak your dried chickpeas overnight or for at least 8 to 12 hours. Note that the chickpeas will triple in size, so cover them with plenty of water. Then drain and rinse them.","name":"Soak","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#wprm-recipe-34477-step-0-0","image":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2024\\/06\\/How-To-Make-Falafel-1.jpg"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Pulse all the ingredients to a food processor. Add the chickpeas, onion, parsley, cilantro, garlic, green pepper, and spices to a food processor. I recommend roughly chopping up the onion, herbs, and pepper before adding for the best texture. Then, pulse the food processor but do not blend completely. The final mixture should resemble coarse sand.","name":"Add","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#wprm-recipe-34477-step-0-1","image":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2024\\/06\\/How-To-Make-Falafel-2.jpg"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Chill the falafel. Transfer the falafel mixture to a bowl and add the chickpea flour and baking soda. Stir together, then cover or add a lid and refrigerate the mixture for 30 minutes to one hour.","name":"Stir","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#wprm-recipe-34477-step-0-2","image":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2024\\/06\\/How-To-Make-Falafel-4.jpg"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Shape the falafel. Use your hands, an ice cream scoop or falafel scoop to form the falafel into balls or patties. If you find the mixture is too wet, you can add another tablespoon of chickpea flour. If it&#39;s too dry and crumbly, you can add a teaspoon or two of water or lemon juice.","name":"Scoop","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#wprm-recipe-34477-step-0-3","image":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2024\\/06\\/How-To-Make-Falafel-8.jpg"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Cook the falafel. Once the falafel are formed, you can cook them by your preferred method mentioned above. To deep fry the falafel, add about 3 inches of oil to a pot on medium heat. Heat the oil to 350\\u00b0F (175\\u00b0C). Cook the falafel in batches (about 6 to 8 at a time) for 1 to 2 minutes or until golden.","name":"Cook","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#wprm-recipe-34477-step-0-4","image":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2024\\/06\\/How-To-Make-Falafel-5.jpg"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Remove the falafel. Use a skimmer to check the color of the falafel and make sure they don&#39;t overcook. Then remove them to a paper towel-lined plate.","name":"Remove","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#wprm-recipe-34477-step-0-5","image":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2024\\/06\\/How-To-Make-Falafel-6.jpg"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Serve the falafel immediately, while warm and crispy on the outside. They&#39;re delicious served with tahini sauce as well.","name":"Serve","url":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#wprm-recipe-34477-step-0-6","image":"https:\\/\\/i2.wp.com\\/www.downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2024\\/06\\/How-To-Make-Falafel-7.jpg"}],"aggregateRating":{"@type":"AggregateRating","ratingValue":"4.94","ratingCount":"511","reviewCount":"8"},"review":[{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"If I can\\u2019t find Chile pepper at the local store, what can I replace it with ? \\u2728","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Christy"},"datePublished":"2026-06-05"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"Herbs I had in the garden were basil, cilantro and dill. Also added pistachios\\r\\nYummy","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Chris Cz"},"datePublished":"2026-06-03"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"Okay. I visited Israel and helped with some summer camps out there way back when I was in college. The food was amazing, and I was expecting to be able to find someone somewhere with an authentic restaurant serving the amazing food I had overseas. Nope. Nada. Nothing has come close to the flavor, texture, and satisfaction of the falafel I had in Nazareth. Until now. I made these today, and I felt like I was transported back 20 years to the falafel guy\\u2019s cart taking my first ever bite of falafel. These are amazing. I made them with homemade pitas using the recipe from Turkuaz Kitchen for those, and I served this with the lentil salad, the tahini sauce, and tzatziki that I make myself. The meal was a Mediterranean feast in my own home! You will be cooking forever. I mean, I am a seasoned chef, and it took me 5 hours to prepare everything. That is even with making these tahini sauce and preparing the cucumber for tzatziki the night before. It is a long process of a meal, but the payout is worth it. 100%. I don\\u2019t know why I assumed that cilantro is strictly for Mexican food because it was heavenly in the falafel. I don\\u2019t like peppers and went ahead and included a jalapeno without the seeds, and it really did help with the flavor. Don\\u2019t leave out the pepper! I don\\u2019t care if it takes me days to make this meal. I\\u2019m utilizing my summer garden and absolutely making this a staple in my house. Thank you for ALL the recipes! The lentil salad was divine with it!","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Christie"},"datePublished":"2026-05-21"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"This falafel recipe is a true gem, it is 100% authentic taste (and I\\u2019ve lived in Israel, so I\\u2019ve had A LOT of falafel in my life). Very easy to make, remains vibrant green once cooked and is so tasty I start eating it straight out of the fryer :)","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Lilly"},"datePublished":"2026-05-14"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"This is my go to recipe. I\\u2019ve been making them for 5 years. Today, I followed the recipe precisely and got perfect results. In the past, I\\u2019ve had crumbly mixtures but that\\u2019s usually because I don\\u2019t blend them enough-in the food processor. I make the tahini sauce as well. Yum!!!","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Tea Rose"},"datePublished":"2026-04-26"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"I made this- and we are putting this into our rotation along with our roasted veggies, tahini, tzatziki. I\'m so glad to find this! I\'ve been using a dry mix for years- and there is no comparison to this fresh herby deliciousness! \\r\\nOurs was a little wet- as I used almond flour- and perhaps my herbs were still wet from rinsing. I also let it sit overnight in the fridge before using it- maybe if used right away, the wetness would have been less. I\'m not sure. I had to use about 6 T of almond flour and a little bit of olive oil to create a little structure. I would almost add an egg for binding- as we aren\'t vegan. Do you think that would help. I\'ve frozen the rest of the little discs... and we made them small- so this recipe made about 30 falafel.","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Jana Throckmorton"},"datePublished":"2026-04-25"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"No joke, this recipe made the best falafel I\'ve ever had, and it came from my very own kitchen! I can\'t thank you enough for this recipe. The falafel was so tender, herby and incredibly flavorful. I put my trust into this, and made a double batch. So glad I did. I froze a bunch of uncooked balls, and they fried up as well as the fresh ones did, so I now have falafel at the ready whenever I want it! I also made the tahini sauce linked in this recipe. Together they made the ultimate falafel experience. So amazing.","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Isabelle"},"datePublished":"2026-04-24"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"Love this falafel recipe! It\'s my go to for making falafels, and I\'ve made them for myself, friends and extended family members (including preteens and teens) and everyone loved them. \\r\\nWe make it as detailed, and pan fry them usually. Always delicious!","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Megan"},"datePublished":"2026-04-22"}],"recipeCategory":["Main Course"],"recipeCuisine":["Mediterranean","Middle Eastern"],"keywords":"Falafel, Falafel Recipe, How to Make Falafel","nutrition":{"@type":"NutritionInformation","calories":"48 kcal","carbohydrateContent":"8 g","proteinContent":"3 g","fatContent":"1 g","saturatedFatContent":"0.1 g","sodiumContent":"166 mg","fiberContent":"2 g","sugarContent":"2 g","unsaturatedFatContent":"0.5 g","servingSize":"1 serving"},"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#recipe","isPartOf":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/"},"mainEntityOfPage":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/"},{"@type":"VideoObject","@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/#video","name":"Most Delicious Falafel Recipe (Fried or Baked) | Downshiftology","isPartOf":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/recipes\\/falafel\\/"},"thumbnailUrl":"https:\\/\\/downshiftology.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2019\\/07\\/aqd0ndqgpg0.jpg","description":"Are you ready for the best falafel you\'ve ever tasted? Falafel are delicious balls of chickpea and herb goodness in Middle Eastern cooking.","uploadDate":"2024-09-06","width":480,"height":270,"embedUrl":"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/embed\\/aQD0ndQGpG0","duration":"PT8M50S","isFamilyFriendly":true,"inLanguage":"en-US"}]}',
                'image' => 'https://i2.wp.com/www.downshiftology.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/Falafel-main-2.jpg',
            'ingredients' => '["1 cup dried chickpeas (soaked overnight (don&#x27;t use canned chickpeas))","\\u00bd cup roughly chopped onion","1 cup roughly chopped parsley (about a one large bunch)","1 cup roughly chopped cilantro (about a one large bunch)","1 small green chile pepper (serrano or jalapeno pepper)","3 garlic cloves","1 teaspoon cumin","1 teaspoon salt","\\u00bd teaspoon cardamom","\\u00bc teaspoon black pepper","2 tablespoons chickpea flour (or other flour)","\\u00bd teaspoon baking soda","oil for frying"]',
            'directions' => '["Soak your dried chickpeas overnight or for at least 8 to 12 hours. Note that the chickpeas will triple in size, so cover them with plenty of water. Then drain and rinse them.","Pulse all the ingredients to a food processor. Add the chickpeas, onion, parsley, cilantro, garlic, green pepper, and spices to a food processor. I recommend roughly chopping up the onion, herbs, and pepper before adding for the best texture. Then, pulse the food processor but do not blend completely. The final mixture should resemble coarse sand.","Chill the falafel. Transfer the falafel mixture to a bowl and add the chickpea flour and baking soda. Stir together, then cover or add a lid and refrigerate the mixture for 30 minutes to one hour.","Shape the falafel. Use your hands, an ice cream scoop or falafel scoop to form the falafel into balls or patties. If you find the mixture is too wet, you can add another tablespoon of chickpea flour. If it&#39;s too dry and crumbly, you can add a teaspoon or two of water or lemon juice.","Cook the falafel. Once the falafel are formed, you can cook them by your preferred method mentioned above. To deep fry the falafel, add about 3 inches of oil to a pot on medium heat. Heat the oil to 350\\u00b0F (175\\u00b0C). Cook the falafel in batches (about 6 to 8 at a time) for 1 to 2 minutes or until golden.","Remove the falafel. Use a skimmer to check the color of the falafel and make sure they don&#39;t overcook. Then remove them to a paper towel-lined plate.","Serve the falafel immediately, while warm and crispy on the outside. They&#39;re delicious served with tahini sauce as well."]',
