\\/#organization","name":"Rainbow Plant Life","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","inLanguage":"en-US","@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/#\\/schema\\/logo\\/image\\/","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2021\\/08\\/RPL-Logo-SQUARE.png","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2021\\/08\\/RPL-Logo-SQUARE.png","width":453,"height":453,"caption":"Rainbow Plant Life"},"image":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/#\\/schema\\/logo\\/image\\/"},"sameAs":["https:\\/\\/www.facebook.com\\/rainbowplantlife","https:\\/\\/www.instagram.com\\/rainbowplantlife\\/","https:\\/\\/pinterest.com\\/rainbowplantlife\\/","https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/channel\\/UCDbZvuDA_tZ6XP5wKKFuemQ"]},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/#\\/schema\\/person\\/7943c9c8c6cf9cec898fd08ad2629b4d","name":"Nisha Vora","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","inLanguage":"en-US","@id":"https:\\/\\/secure.gravatar.com\\/avatar\\/d8da3061e552a5f9f06550473846d6956b8804d85b2bcec84006babc4a85262e?s=96&d=mm&r=g","url":"https:\\/\\/secure.gravatar.com\\/avatar\\/d8da3061e552a5f9f06550473846d6956b8804d85b2bcec84006babc4a85262e?s=96&d=mm&r=g","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/secure.gravatar.com\\/avatar\\/d8da3061e552a5f9f06550473846d6956b8804d85b2bcec84006babc4a85262e?s=96&d=mm&r=g","caption":"Nisha Vora"},"sameAs":["https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/about-nisha\\/","https:\\/\\/x.com\\/rainbowplantlife@gmail.com"],"url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/about-nisha\\/"},{"@type":"Question","@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675262492338","position":1,"url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675262492338","name":"Can I substitute the coconut milk with something else?\\u00a0","answerCount":1,"acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes, cashew cream makes for a lovely substitute here. To make the cashew cream:\\u00a0<br\\/><br\\/>1. Soak <strong>\\u00bd cup (70g) of <em>raw, unsalted<\\/em> cashews<\\/strong> in water overnight, or do a quick soak by adding them to a saucepan, covering with water, and boiling for 15 minutes. Drain the cashews and rinse well.\\u00a0<br\\/><br\\/>2. Add <strong>6 tablespoons (90 mL) of water<\\/strong> to a small-capacity high-powered blender (small blender jug, 32 oz \\/ 1L or smaller). Add the cashews, <strong>1 TBSP of freshly squeezed lemon juice,<\\/strong> and <strong>\\u00bd tsp kosher salt<\\/strong>.\\u00a0<br\\/><br\\/>3. Blend for about 2 minutes, starting on low and gradually moving up to high speed. Scrape down the sides as you go and blend until it\\u2019s completely smooth and no cashew bits remain.<br\\/><br\\/><em>Note<\\/em>: If you only have a large-capacity high-powered blender, you\\u2019ll need to double the cashew cream, as there isn\\u2019t enough liquid here to blend in a large container. A food processor is a great alternative, but the texture won\\u2019t be as silky smooth. Blend the ingredients for approximately 4 minutes.","inLanguage":"en-US"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Question","@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675262698066","position":2,"url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675262698066","name":"What tahini brands do you recommend?","answerCount":1,"acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"You can use any tahini brand that isn\\u2019t bitter in flavor. However, since the tahini isn\\u2019t a main flavor component here like it is in <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/beet-hummus\\">hummus<\\/a>, you\\u2019re welcome to be flexible in the brand you use.<br><br>In the RPL kitchen, we often use <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/geni.us\\/G8PBg\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\\">Al Kanater<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/geni.us\\/f3naBvA\\" type=\\"link\\" id=\\"https:\\/\\/geni.us\\/f3naBvA\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\\">Beirut sesame paste<\\/a>, and <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/geni.us\\/moadI\\" type=\\"link\\" id=\\"https:\\/\\/geni.us\\/moadI\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\\">Al Arz<\\/a>. ","inLanguage":"en-US"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Question","@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675264302943","position":3,"url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675264302943","name":"Is this chickpea curry spicy?","answerCount":1,"acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"It\'s fairly mild, but it can be as spicy or as mild as you want it to be. <br\\/><br\\/>For very mild heat, use 1 serrano pepper (or jalape\\u00f1o). While these peppers are quite spicy on their own, the coconut milk tempers the heat very well. <br\\/><br\\/>If you enjoy heat, use 2 to 3 peppers (3 is my preference for spicy!).\\u00a0<br\\/><br\\/>Remember: the white membranes inside peppers have most of the heat. So if you\'re uncertain about how spicy it will be, remove some of them to moderate the heat.","inLanguage":"en-US"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Question","@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675262711329","position":4,"url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675262711329","name":"How long does this curry last? How should I store and reheat it?\\u00a0","answerCount":1,"acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The leftovers stay fresh for up to 5 days when stored in an airtight container in the fridge. It also freezes well in about 3 months. I recommend freezing the curry in single-serve portions using <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/amzn.to\\/3IHTgDY\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\\">Souper Cubes<\\/a> to speed up the defrost.<br><br>The leftovers thicken considerably in the fridge. But once you reheat it in a saucepan, it loosens up. If needed, add a splash of water or veggie broth to loosen it more.\\u00a0<br>","inLanguage":"en-US"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Question","@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675262731308","position":5,"url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#faq-question-1675262731308","name":"What should I serve this with?","answerCount":1,"acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Scoop the curry into bowls with cooked white basmati rice (the classic), or brown rice or a whole grain like farro or quinoa. If you have extra time, take every serving over the top with some <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/vegan-naan\\/\\">vegan naan<\\/a> (it\'s perfect for sopping up the delicious gravy!). ","inLanguage":"en-US"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Recipe","name":"Chickpea Curry","author":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/#\\/schema\\/person\\/7943c9c8c6cf9cec898fd08ad2629b4d"},"description":"This creamy, dreamy Chickpea Curry makes for a gourmet, restaurant-quality yet approachable meal that\\u2019s on the table in an hour. Featuring bold Indian flavors and a taste of healthy indulgence, it&#039;ll quickly become a new staple in your dinner rotation.","datePublished":"2023-02-02T01:35:11+00:00","image":["https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/02\\/chickpea-curry-cover-photo-1-of-1.jpg","https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/02\\/chickpea-curry-cover-photo-1-of-1-500x500.jpg","https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/02\\/chickpea-curry-cover-photo-1-of-1-500x375.jpg","https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/wp-content\\/uploads\\/2023\\/02\\/chickpea-curry-cover-photo-1-of-1-480x270.jpg"],"recipeYield":["6","6 with rice"],"prepTime":"PT25M","cookTime":"PT35M","totalTime":"PT60M","recipeIngredient":["2 tablespoons avocado oil or neutral-flavored oil of choice","2 teaspoons coriander seeds ((Note 1))","1 heaping teaspoon cumin seeds ((Note 1))","15 to 20 fresh curry leaves, or 30 dried curry leaves ((optional but recommended, Note 2))","1 large yellow or red onion, (finely diced)","6 garlic cloves, (minced)","2- inch piece fresh ginger, (minced or grated)","1 to 3 serrano peppers, (diced (1 adds mild heat; 3 for spicy!!))","2 tablespoons tomato paste","\\u00bd pound (227g) Roma tomatoes (2 roma tomatoes), (diced)","2 teaspoons Diamond Crystal kosher salt ((Note 3) )","1 (13.5 oz \\/400 mL) can full-fat coconut milk ((Note 4))","\\u00bd cup (120 mL) water ((Note 5))","2 (15 oz \\/425g) cans chickpeas, ( drained and rinsed)","3 tablespoons tahini, (well-stirred)","1\\/2 teaspoon organic cane sugar, (brown sugar, or coconut sugar)","1 small head of Swiss chard or lacinato kale ((Note 6))","2 teaspoons garam masala","Freshly squeezed lemon or lime juice, (\\u00bd to 1 tablespoon, to taste)","1 big handful of cilantro leaves and tender stems, (chopped)","1 big handful of fresh mint leaves, (chopped)","1 \\u00bd teaspoons curry powder","1 teaspoon ground coriander","\\u00bd teaspoon ground cinnamon","1\\/2 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg","\\u00bc teaspoon ground turmeric","Lots of freshly ground black pepper"],"recipeInstructions":[{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Keep a small bowl of water nearby for deglazing. Heat the oil in a 12-inch heavy-bottomed saut\\u00e9 pan or medium Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Once hot, add the cumin and coriander seeds for about 1 minute, tossing frequently, or until aromatic and darker by a few shades but don\\u2019t let them burn!Add the curry leaves: if using fresh leaves, cover the pan immediately and stand back to prevent oil splatter. Cook for just 20 seconds to prevent burning. For dry leaves, cook a little longer.","name":"Keep a small bowl of water nearby for deglazing. Heat the oil in a 12-inch heavy-bottomed saut\\u00e9 pan or medium Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Once hot, add the cumin and coriander seeds for about 1 minute, tossing frequently, or until aromatic and darker by a few shades but don\\u2019t let them burn!Add the curry leaves: if using fresh leaves, cover the pan immediately and stand back to prevent oil splatter. Cook for just 20 seconds to prevent burning. For dry leaves, cook a little longer.","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#wprm-recipe-29821-step-0-0"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Add the onions with a big pinch of salt and cook for 5 minutes, until starting to get some color. If the spices start to darken, lower the heat to medium. Add a splash of water as needed to prevent onions from browning. Add garlic, ginger, serrano peppers, and cook for 1 to 2 minutes, stirring frequently.","name":"Add the onions with a big pinch of salt and cook for 5 minutes, until starting to get some color. If the spices start to darken, lower the heat to medium. Add a splash of water as needed to prevent onions from browning. Add garlic, ginger, serrano peppers, and cook for 1 to 2 minutes, stirring frequently.","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#wprm-recipe-29821-step-0-1"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Add Ground Spices and tomato paste and stir frequently for 90 seconds. If it dries out, add a splash of water. Add tomatoes + 2 teaspoons kosher salt. Use tomato juices to scrape up browned bits. Cook for 5 minutes, or until tomatoes are soft and the oil starts to release from them.","name":"Add Ground Spices and tomato paste and stir frequently for 90 seconds. If it dries out, add a splash of water. Add tomatoes + 2 teaspoons kosher salt. Use tomato juices to scrape up browned bits. Cook for 5 minutes, or until tomatoes are soft and the oil starts to release from them.","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#wprm-recipe-29821-step-0-2"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Pour in chickpeas, coconut milk, water, tahini, and sugar. Stir well and bring to a simmer. Cover and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes, opening the pot to stir occasionally.","name":"Pour in chickpeas, coconut milk, water, tahini, and sugar. Stir well and bring to a simmer. Cover and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes, opening the pot to stir occasionally.","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#wprm-recipe-29821-step-0-3"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Meanwhile, rinse Swiss chard (or kale) and cilantro and mint. For the greens, remove the center ribs and discard. Roll the leaves and up slice the leaves very thinly. Chop the cilantro and mint.","name":"Meanwhile, rinse Swiss chard (or kale) and cilantro and mint. For the greens, remove the center ribs and discard. Roll the leaves and up slice the leaves very thinly. Chop the cilantro and mint.","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#wprm-recipe-29821-step-0-4"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"After the simmer time, add the greens. Simmer until tender and wilted, 4 to 5 minutes. Stir in the garam masala to combine.","name":"After the simmer time, add the greens. Simmer until tender and wilted, 4 to 5 minutes. Stir in the garam masala to combine.","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#wprm-recipe-29821-step-0-5"},{"@type":"HowToStep","text":"Off the heat, squeeze in a little lemon or lime juice, cilantro, and mint. Season to taste with salt (about \\u00bd teaspoon kosher salt). Rest for 5 to 15 minutes to allow flavors to meld. Serve with cooked rice or flatbread.","name":"Off the heat, squeeze in a little lemon or lime juice, cilantro, and mint. Season to taste with salt (about \\u00bd teaspoon kosher salt). Rest for 5 to 15 minutes to allow flavors to meld. Serve with cooked rice or flatbread.","url":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#wprm-recipe-29821-step-0-6"}],"aggregateRating":{"@type":"AggregateRating","ratingValue":"4.98","ratingCount":"410","reviewCount":"7"},"review":[{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"Made this today - enjoying it now. I did cheat by using a slow cooker. I used dry chickpeas and cooked those on high for 3 hours, then added almost everything to the slow cooker (except greens &amp; garam masala) and cooked on low for another 5 hours. Next time I\'ll use 1 serrano instead of 2, since it was a bit spicy for me. And next time I might cheat even more by using a food processor instead of doing the knife work, which should make this almost a \\"hands off\\" recipe. And I also plan to double the recipe and freeze it in some Souper Cubes for have easy meals for weeks. Thanks.","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"MrTonyD"},"datePublished":"2026-06-16"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"I just made this 2 days ago, I didn\'t have curry leaves and forgot to stop on my way home so I omitted them, I also subbed spinach for the swiss chard. Absolutely delicious and even better for lunch the next day!","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Karie"},"datePublished":"2026-06-03"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"Great recipe!","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Alexandra Hall\\u00e9"},"datePublished":"2026-06-03"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"I love this recipe. I do agree that the prep time is more than what was listed but I find that doing the prep earlier (the spice blends) helps as well as freezing the chiles and the ginger to make them last longer. I make this recipe at least once a month and I always look forward to it!","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Isabella"},"datePublished":"2026-05-27"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"Dear Nisha,\\r\\n\\r\\nI\'ve made your curry for the second time now and its one of my favorite dishes to eat right now. Its soo rich and decadent, could be straight from a restaurant!! The fats from the coconut milk and tahini, mix of spices and freshness of the herbs and lime really lift the dish on another level with a complexity of flavours that is to die for. And its fairly low maintenance, I only had to chop the alliums and ginger, thats basically it. \\r\\nThis is getting into my regular meal rotation! I try to freeze a portion of the meals I cook and this curry is one of freezer meals I look forward to the most.","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Jen"},"datePublished":"2026-05-23"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"3"},"reviewBody":"Delicious, but all the food prep and spices is Exhausting!","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Leah"},"datePublished":"2026-05-18"},{"@type":"Review","reviewRating":{"@type":"Rating","ratingValue":"5"},"reviewBody":"Delicious and easy steps to follow.","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Marie"},"datePublished":"2026-05-05"}],"recipeCategory":["Dinner"],"recipeCuisine":["Indian-Inspired"],"suitableForDiet":["https:\\/\\/schema.org\\/GlutenFreeDiet","https:\\/\\/schema.org\\/VeganDiet","https:\\/\\/schema.org\\/VegetarianDiet"],"keywords":"chickpea curry, chickpea curry recipe, vegan chickpea curry, vegan curry with chickpeas","nutrition":{"@type":"NutritionInformation","calories":"360 kcal","carbohydrateContent":"33 g","proteinContent":"12 g","fatContent":"22 g","saturatedFatContent":"11 g","sodiumContent":"1352 mg","fiberContent":"10 g","sugarContent":"4 g","unsaturatedFatContent":"10 g","servingSize":"1 serving"},"@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#recipe","isPartOf":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/#article"},"mainEntityOfPage":"https:\\/\\/rainbowplantlife.com\\/chickpea-curry\\/"}]}',
                'image' => 'https://rainbowplantlife.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/chickpea-curry-cover-photo-1-of-1.jpg',
            'ingredients' => '["2 tablespoons avocado oil or neutral-flavored oil of choice","2 teaspoons coriander seeds ((Note 1))","1 heaping teaspoon cumin seeds ((Note 1))","15 to 20 fresh curry leaves, or 30 dried curry leaves ((optional but recommended, Note 2))","1 large yellow or red onion, (finely diced)","6 garlic cloves, (minced)","2- inch piece fresh ginger, (minced or grated)","1 to 3 serrano peppers, (diced (1 adds mild heat; 3 for spicy!!))","2 tablespoons tomato paste","\\u00bd pound (227g) Roma tomatoes (2 roma tomatoes), (diced)","2 teaspoons Diamond Crystal kosher salt ((Note 3) )","1 (13.5 oz \\/400 mL) can full-fat coconut milk ((Note 4))","\\u00bd cup (120 mL) water ((Note 5))","2 (15 oz \\/425g) cans chickpeas, ( drained and rinsed)","3 tablespoons tahini, (well-stirred)","1\\/2 teaspoon organic cane sugar, (brown sugar, or coconut sugar)","1 small head of Swiss chard or lacinato kale ((Note 6))","2 teaspoons garam masala","Freshly squeezed lemon or lime juice, (\\u00bd to 1 tablespoon, to taste)","1 big handful of cilantro leaves and tender stems, (chopped)","1 big handful of fresh mint leaves, (chopped)","1 \\u00bd teaspoons curry powder","1 teaspoon ground coriander","\\u00bd teaspoon ground cinnamon","1\\/2 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg","\\u00bc teaspoon ground turmeric","Lots of freshly ground black pepper"]',
            'directions' => '["Keep a small bowl of water nearby for deglazing. Heat the oil in a 12-inch heavy-bottomed saut\\u00e9 pan or medium Dutch oven over medium-high heat. Once hot, add the cumin and coriander seeds for about 1 minute, tossing frequently, or until aromatic and darker by a few shades but don\\u2019t let them burn!Add the curry leaves: if using fresh leaves, cover the pan immediately and stand back to prevent oil splatter. Cook for just 20 seconds to prevent burning. For dry leaves, cook a little longer.","Add the onions with a big pinch of salt and cook for 5 minutes, until starting to get some color. If the spices start to darken, lower the heat to medium. Add a splash of water as needed to prevent onions from browning. Add garlic, ginger, serrano peppers, and cook for 1 to 2 minutes, stirring frequently.","Add Ground Spices and tomato paste and stir frequently for 90 seconds. If it dries out, add a splash of water. Add tomatoes + 2 teaspoons kosher salt. Use tomato juices to scrape up browned bits. Cook for 5 minutes, or until tomatoes are soft and the oil starts to release from them.","Pour in chickpeas, coconut milk, water, tahini, and sugar. Stir well and bring to a simmer. Cover and simmer for 15 to 20 minutes, opening the pot to stir occasionally.","Meanwhile, rinse Swiss chard (or kale) and cilantro and mint. For the greens, remove the center ribs and discard. Roll the leaves and up slice the leaves very thinly. Chop the cilantro and mint.","After the simmer time, add the greens. Simmer until tender and wilted, 4 to 5 minutes. Stir in the garam masala to combine.","Off the heat, squeeze in a little lemon or lime juice, cilantro, and mint. Season to taste with salt (about \\u00bd teaspoon kosher salt). Rest for 5 to 15 minutes to allow flavors to meld. Serve with cooked rice or flatbread."]',
                'nutrition' => '[{"@type":"NutritionInformation","calories":"360 kcal","carbohydrateContent":"33 g","proteinContent":"12 g","fatContent":"22 g","saturatedFatContent":"11 g","sodiumContent":"1352 mg","fiberContent":"10 g","sugarContent":"4 g","unsaturatedFatContent":"10 g","servingSize":"1 serving"}]',
