                'url' => 'https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1027352-dan-dan-noodle-salad',
                'site_domain' => 'https//cooking.nytimes.com',
                'site_name' => 'Hetty Lui McKinnon',
                'user_id' => 1,
            'description' => 'Turns out, dan dan noodles work well as a salad, in this recipe adapted from my cookbook “Linger: Salads, Sweets and Stories to Savor” (Knopf, 2025), as the signature punchy sauce made with sesame paste and chile oil transforms nicely into an assertive dressing. Curly and chewy ramen noodles cling perfectly to the sauce, but you could really use any noodle you like, including instant noodles, udon or thick rice noodles. Adapt this salad throughout the year by adding seasonal vegetables such as mushrooms, broccoli, cauliﬂower, sugar snap peas, snow peas, spinach or green beans.',
            'content' => '{"@context":"http:\\/\\/schema.org","@id":"nyt:\\/\\/recipe\\/d7358f41-7bd3-5f4f-afc3-c4520d7b98dc","@type":"Recipe","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/cooking.nytimes.com\\/recipes\\/1027352-dan-dan-noodle-salad","@type":"WebPage","name":"Dan Dan Noodle Salad"},"url":"https:\\/\\/cooking.nytimes.com\\/recipes\\/1027352-dan-dan-noodle-salad","name":"Dan Dan Noodle Salad","description":"Turns out, dan dan noodles work well as a salad, in this recipe adapted from my cookbook \\u201cLinger: Salads, Sweets and Stories to Savor\\u201d (Knopf, 2025), as the signature punchy sauce made with sesame paste and chile oil transforms nicely into an assertive dressing. Curly and chewy ramen noodles cling perfectly to the sauce, but you could really use any noodle you like, including instant noodles, udon or thick rice noodles. Adapt this salad throughout the year by adding seasonal vegetables such as mushrooms, broccoli, cauli\\ufb02ower, sugar snap peas, snow peas, spinach or green beans.","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Hetty Lui McKinnon"},"image":[{"@id":"nyt:\\/\\/image\\/d8b7a9c6-bc8c-5a76-816d-904e9684bb2d#videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600","@type":"ImageObject","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/static01.nyt.com\\/images\\/2025\\/09\\/25\\/multimedia\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg","creditText":"Linda Xiao for The New York Times. Food Stylist: Monica Pierini. Prop Stylist: Sophia Eleni Pappas.","dateModified":"2025-09-25T19:21:37.911Z","datePublished":"2025-09-23T17:42:08.000Z","height":"900","representativeOfPage":true,"uploadDate":"2025-09-23T17:42:08.000Z","url":"https:\\/\\/static01.nyt.com\\/images\\/2025\\/09\\/25\\/multimedia\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg","width":"1600"},{"@id":"nyt:\\/\\/image\\/d8b7a9c6-bc8c-5a76-816d-904e9684bb2d#googleFourByThree","@type":"ImageObject","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/static01.nyt.com\\/images\\/2025\\/09\\/25\\/multimedia\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-googleFourByThree.jpg","creditText":"Linda Xiao for The New York Times. Food Stylist: Monica Pierini. Prop Stylist: Sophia Eleni Pappas.","dateModified":"2025-09-25T19:21:37.911Z","datePublished":"2025-09-23T17:42:08.000Z","height":"600","representativeOfPage":true,"uploadDate":"2025-09-23T17:42:08.000Z","url":"https:\\/\\/static01.nyt.com\\/images\\/2025\\/09\\/25\\/multimedia\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-googleFourByThree.jpg","width":"800"},{"@id":"nyt:\\/\\/image\\/d8b7a9c6-bc8c-5a76-816d-904e9684bb2d#mediumSquareAt3X","@type":"ImageObject","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/static01.nyt.com\\/images\\/2025\\/09\\/25\\/multimedia\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-mediumSquareAt3X.jpg","creditText":"Linda Xiao for The New York Times. Food Stylist: Monica Pierini. Prop Stylist: Sophia Eleni Pappas.","dateModified":"2025-09-25T19:21:37.911Z","datePublished":"2025-09-23T17:42:08.000Z","height":"1800","representativeOfPage":true,"uploadDate":"2025-09-23T17:42:08.000Z","url":"https:\\/\\/static01.nyt.com\\/images\\/2025\\/09\\/25\\/multimedia\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-mediumSquareAt3X.jpg","width":"1800"},{"@id":"nyt:\\/\\/image\\/d8b7a9c6-bc8c-5a76-816d-904e9684bb2d#facebookJumbo","@type":"ImageObject","contentUrl":"https:\\/\\/static01.nyt.com\\/images\\/2025\\/09\\/25\\/multimedia\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-facebookJumbo.jpg","creditText":"Linda Xiao for The New York Times. Food Stylist: Monica Pierini. Prop Stylist: Sophia Eleni Pappas.","dateModified":"2025-09-25T19:21:37.911Z","datePublished":"2025-09-23T17:42:08.000Z","height":"549","representativeOfPage":true,"uploadDate":"2025-09-23T17:42:08.000Z","url":"https:\\/\\/static01.nyt.com\\/images\\/2025\\/09\\/25\\/multimedia\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf\\/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-facebookJumbo.jpg","width":"1050"}],"prepTime":"PT5M","cookTime":"PT20M","totalTime":"PT25M","recipeYield":"4 servings","recipeCuisine":"","recipeCategory":"dinner, easy, lunch, quick, weeknight, noodles, main course, side dish","keywords":"bok choy, budget, chile crisp, chile oil, chinese inspired, corn, party, ramen noodle, salad, sesame paste, stovetop, dairy-free, vegan, vegetarian","aggregateRating":{"@type":"AggregateRating","ratingValue":5,"ratingCount":804},"nutrition":{"@context":"http:\\/\\/schema.org","@type":"NutritionInformation","calories":500,"unsaturatedFatContent":"12 grams","carbohydrateContent":"71 grams","cholesterolContent":null,"fatContent":"20 grams","fiberContent":"6 grams","proteinContent":"14 grams","saturatedFatContent":"7 grams","sodiumContent":"1572 milligrams","sugarContent":"7 grams","transFatContent":"0 grams"},"recipeIngredient":["Sea salt","10 ounces baby bok choy (about 4)","10 ounces fresh or frozen ramen noodles","2 cups\\/10 ounces fresh or canned corn kernels (or thawed from frozen)","2 tablespoons toasted white sesame seeds","2 scallions, thinly sliced","2 tablespoons Chinese sesame paste or tahini","2 tablespoons chile oil or chile crisp, plus more for serving","1 tablespoon soy sauce or tamari","2 teaspoons black or rice vinegar","2 teaspoons sugar","1 garlic clove, grated","2 to 3 tablespoons unsweetened nondairy milk (such as soy or oat) or water"],"recipeInstructions":[{"@context":"http:\\/\\/schema.org","@type":"HowToStep","text":"Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil.\\u00a0"},{"@context":"http:\\/\\/schema.org","@type":"HowToStep","text":"Separate the white and green parts of the baby bok choy. Slice the white parts into thick pieces. Place in a colander and rinse well to remove any dirt or sediments. Drain."},{"@context":"http:\\/\\/schema.org","@type":"HowToStep","text":"Add the ramen to the boiling water and cook until al dente according to packet directions. About 1\\u00bd\\u00a0minutes before the noodles are ready, add the white parts of the baby bok choy and the corn. Just before everything is ready, throw in the green bok choy leaves and blanch until they are wilted, about 20\\u00a0seconds. Drain immediately and refresh under cold running water, then leave to drain again. Let cool while you make the dressing."},{"@context":"http:\\/\\/schema.org","@type":"HowToStep","text":"Make the dan dan dressing: In a small bowl, whisk together the sesame paste, chile oil, soy sauce, vinegar, sugar and garlic until a chunky paste forms. Add 2\\u00a0tablespoons of the milk and whisk, adding another tablespoon if needed, until the dressing is smooth and pourable. The dressing should be the consistency of cream. (The dressing can be prepared up to 2 days ahead and stored in a sealed jar or airtight container in the fridge. It will thicken up, so add a splash or two of milk or water to loosen it up before adding to the noodles.)"},{"@context":"http:\\/\\/schema.org","@type":"HowToStep","text":"In a large shallow bowl, place the ramen noodles, greens and corn. Add the dressing and toss to coat. Top with the sesame seeds, scallions and a few drops of chile oil. Taste and season with salt if needed. Serve at room temperature."}],"publisher":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/cooking.nytimes.com\\/#publisher","@type":"Organization","name":"NYT Cooking"},"datePublished":"2025-09-25T00:00:00.000Z","dateModified":"2025-10-01T14:13:22.000Z","review":[{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Cathy"},"reviewBody":"Has anyone made in advance..a day or two?","datePublished":"2025-11-10T16:34:36.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Sabrina"},"reviewBody":"Delicious! I added some tofu and a little more soy sauce to compensate. It keeps really well in the fridge for lunches for the week too. I dressed everything when I first made it, and the texture was still good throughout the week.","datePublished":"2025-11-07T17:35:46.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Katie"},"reviewBody":"I liked the dressing, but cooking the bok choy stems somehow got them super water-logged. Next time instead of adding them to the past water, I may just put them in a colander and slowly drain the noodles over the bok choy.","datePublished":"2025-11-05T23:51:24.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Amanda"},"reviewBody":"An absolute keeper.\\nNot to out myself as being low class, but I don\'t even know what fresh ramen is. I used 3.5 packs on instant ramen and it tasted great. Next time I\'d add a cup of edamame to it and top with a fried or soft boiled egg for protein. I increased sauce by 50% but it could even be doubled.","datePublished":"2025-11-05T21:51:54.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"sslee"},"reviewBody":"Adaptable base recipe. Double the sauce. I\\u2019ll never understand why people with a food allergy ask recipe writers what they can sub for X instead - you\\u2019re the one with the allergy, become the expert on what you can use (and any modifications that might entail) so you can make whatever you want and not be beholden to the suggestions of someone who developed a recipe using something else and won\\u2019t have tested it with whatever you need to use.","datePublished":"2025-11-05T20:07:46.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Lydia"},"reviewBody":"Easy and excellent! Doubled the dressing...","datePublished":"2025-11-04T05:20:20.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Roald"},"reviewBody":"Why \\"milk\\" in Dan Dan noodles? I would add 6-8 oz ground beef pork. Note that Szechuan peppercorns commonly include the hard black inner seeds, which need to be removed to avoid grittiness. All you are supposed to eat are the husks.","datePublished":"2025-11-03T02:59:26.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"bubba"},"reviewBody":"This gives me a new leek pasta idea","datePublished":"2025-11-01T18:06:28.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Rose Casa"},"reviewBody":"This was pretty yummy, but I only gave it four stars because I changed it a lot. I skipped the corn and used shelled edamame instead. I made the dressing first. I cooked the edamame in the boiling water first, took it out, then did the bok choy as instructed, took it out. The last thing I did was cook the noodles. When they were ready, I added them to the greens and then put the dressing on it, so that our DanDan noodles were served hot. Everyone loved it!","datePublished":"2025-11-01T16:32:42.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Dan"},"reviewBody":"Looking for ways to improve a 180-year old tradition like dan-dan noodles is like looking for ways to improve Beethoven\'s Ninth Symphony.","datePublished":"2025-11-01T14:54:51.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Travis"},"reviewBody":"definitely double the sauce! you\'ll want some later. Plus, I would recommend giving the colander, or whatever you\'re draining the noodles in, a couple of really good shakes before you add the sauce... I found that the noodles were a little watery and diluted the potency of the sauce when I made this the first time. This is also great reheated in a pan with a squeeze of lime juice at the end!","datePublished":"2025-10-31T17:26:18.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Penni"},"reviewBody":"As suggested by others, I doubled the sauce. Great idea or it would have been too dry. \\nI added tofu and pan fried shrimp and added it to the side of the large serving dish \\nI only had hot sauce on hand and it was just fine","datePublished":"2025-10-27T07:09:16.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Lleity"},"reviewBody":"The best recipe is an adaptable recipe and this is it as many commenters have pointed out with their many adaptations. I used the veggies I had - red cabbage, red onion, cucumbers, fresh jalapenos from the garden - and some fresh cilantro. The dressing is also adaptable - milk or noodle water, peanut butter or tahini. Yummy.","datePublished":"2025-10-26T21:15:35.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"me"},"reviewBody":"Double the sauce!!!","datePublished":"2025-10-26T17:02:39.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"CL"},"reviewBody":"Used a big bunch of tatsoi from my CSA (similar to bok choy) and half frozen corn, half frozen edamame. My chili crisp is spicy so cut back on that a bit. Next time will up the tahini as I like the sesame flavor and add more soy sauce. Seems like it will be very adaptable for seasonal ingredients.","datePublished":"2025-10-25T17:29:57.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"tan"},"reviewBody":"This was a great dish. The sauce is the star and we 1.5x it because I always like extra sauce. We also used water b\\/c we don\\u2019t have fake milk. Added tofu for protein. Will definitely have this recipe on our rotation!","datePublished":"2025-09-29T15:04:19.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Gale"},"reviewBody":"This was as good as it read. I used mushrooms rather than corn, and water (have no fake milk) to thin the dressing - which to me, really made this work.\\nI didn\'t miss the pork at all, and for me, that\'s saying something. It was easy to scale down for one w\\/lunch the next day.","datePublished":"2025-09-29T12:33:21.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"TiCo"},"reviewBody":"Delicious! I thought I had enough ramen noodles (dried) but I didn\'t, so I subbed soba (also dried). I just added a pinch of the sugar instead of the full amount and used half the chili oil. Thank goodness I didn\'t add all the chili oil, it was spicy enough for us. I had a coconut\\/oat milk half and half and that was perfect for the non-dairy milk. I\'ll definitely make it again and try to get fresh ramen noodles. I also might add some tofu and mushrooms.","datePublished":"2025-09-30T00:29:43.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"JackandRosiesma"},"reviewBody":"@tanooh like the idea of adding tofu! Thank you.","datePublished":"2025-10-03T15:23:54.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Nick"},"reviewBody":"@TiCo how did the soba work? Im looking to sub out the ramen totally for dietary reasons.","datePublished":"2025-10-03T16:08:10.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"froggs"},"reviewBody":"This one\\u2019s a real winner! Totally delicious. You can adapt the dressing to suit your taste. I used chile crisp and Szechuan peppercorns. I kept the proportions as written, but doubled the dressing. I used 8 oz dried (not instant) ramen noodles and found that this amount of dressing was perfect.","datePublished":"2025-10-01T01:43:23.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Anon-E-Mouse"},"reviewBody":"Because non-dairy milk is better for the planet and kind to animals.\\n\\nPractically speaking, if this salad is going to be eaten right away, it probably doesn\\u2019t make a difference what milk you use. But if the dish will be at room temperature for a while (for example, you\\u2019re packing the dish for a lunch that doesn\\u2019t get refrigerated or taking it to a potluck where dishes sit out on a table), a non-dairy milk presents less risk of spoilage.\\n\\nI\\u2019ll probably try soy milk for this dish for the protein.","datePublished":"2025-10-03T15:36:38.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"peter"},"reviewBody":"@Anon-E-Mouse non-dairy milks are not necessarily better, often they contain a number of added ingredients, such as preservatives, oils, fats, emulsifiers and artificial stabilisers. Sometimes, they contain sugars - but not always.","datePublished":"2025-10-03T17:00:24.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Cathrene"},"reviewBody":"Dan Dan noodle sauce don\\u2019t have milk or milk substitute. You need dry noodles but not ramen noodles. Then you can use the water from cooking the noodles instead of \\u201dmilk\\u201d, just like in pasta. Also, if you don\\u2019t have sesame paste, you can easily substitute with creamy peanut butter (Skippy or Jif, homogenized peanut butter).","datePublished":"2025-10-03T19:55:19.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Paula CoopTip"},"reviewBody":"I enjoyed this and appreciated how quick it came together. I doubled the sauce since I\\u2019d added extra noodles and veggies but it didn\\u2019t need that much. The sauce is delish and I didn\\u2019t miss any creaminess from the added milk. Water worked well to thin to the right consistency. It\\u2019s a great weeknight meal that provides perfect leftovers for a lunch that doesn\\u2019t need to be heated the next day","datePublished":"2025-10-01T02:43:06.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"KK"},"reviewBody":"@tan an additional way to add protein is frozen edamame. I like to keep some in the freezer and then take out a handful (or more) whenever needed.","datePublished":"2025-10-14T16:23:43.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Donna Willcox"},"reviewBody":"Delicious Sunday family lunch and used leftover sauce to marinate some chicken thighs which I barbecued the next day. Husband and father in law thought it the best chicken ever!","datePublished":"2025-10-02T11:38:37.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"realS"},"reviewBody":"@tan I was wondering how to get some necessary protein into this dish! Thanks","datePublished":"2025-10-04T01:55:20.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"Genevieve"},"reviewBody":"Ha. Eat what you want but meals can be \\u201ccomplete\\u201d without meat, obviously. For example: all of my meals.","datePublished":"2025-10-06T21:49:31.000Z"},{"@type":"Review","author":{"@type":"Person","name":"David"},"reviewBody":"@froggs How many servings when you used 8oz dried ramen noodles?","datePublished":"2025-10-06T16:07:27.000Z"}],"copyrightHolder":{"@id":"https:\\/\\/cooking.nytimes.com\\/#publisher","@type":"Organization","name":"NYT Cooking"},"copyrightYear":2025}',
                'image' => 'https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/09/25/multimedia/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf/25FD-FALL-PARTYrex5-dandan-salad-tqwf-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg',
            'ingredients' => '["Sea salt","10 ounces baby bok choy (about 4)","10 ounces fresh or frozen ramen noodles","2 cups\\/10 ounces fresh or canned corn kernels (or thawed from frozen)","2 tablespoons toasted white sesame seeds","2 scallions, thinly sliced","2 tablespoons Chinese sesame paste or tahini","2 tablespoons chile oil or chile crisp, plus more for serving","1 tablespoon soy sauce or tamari","2 teaspoons black or rice vinegar","2 teaspoons sugar","1 garlic clove, grated","2 to 3 tablespoons unsweetened nondairy milk (such as soy or oat) or water"]',
            'directions' => '["Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil.\\u00a0","Separate the white and green parts of the baby bok choy. Slice the white parts into thick pieces. Place in a colander and rinse well to remove any dirt or sediments. Drain.","Add the ramen to the boiling water and cook until al dente according to packet directions. About 1\\u00bd\\u00a0minutes before the noodles are ready, add the white parts of the baby bok choy and the corn. Just before everything is ready, throw in the green bok choy leaves and blanch until they are wilted, about 20\\u00a0seconds. Drain immediately and refresh under cold running water, then leave to drain again. Let cool while you make the dressing.","Make the dan dan dressing: In a small bowl, whisk together the sesame paste, chile oil, soy sauce, vinegar, sugar and garlic until a chunky paste forms. Add 2\\u00a0tablespoons of the milk and whisk, adding another tablespoon if needed, until the dressing is smooth and pourable. The dressing should be the consistency of cream. (The dressing can be prepared up to 2 days ahead and stored in a sealed jar or airtight container in the fridge. It will thicken up, so add a splash or two of milk or water to loosen it up before adding to the noodles.)","In a large shallow bowl, place the ramen noodles, greens and corn. Add the dressing and toss to coat. Top with the sesame seeds, scallions and a few drops of chile oil. Taste and season with salt if needed. Serve at room temperature."]',
